rdie, France":"Aisne, Picardie, France","Albert, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, France","Clermont-en-Beauvais, Oise, Picardy, France":"Oise, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clermont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Georges, Normand, Pierre, Armand, Edouard, Gaston, Ghislaine, Gilles, Henri, Herve, Jean Francois.","French and English (Middlesex, of Norman and French Huguenot origin): habitational name from any of various places in France called (Le) Clermont, from Old French <i>clair</i>, <i>cler</i> ‘bright, clear’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’, i.e. a hill that could be seen a long way off. Compare   Clairmont  .","English (Middlesex, of Norman and possibly also Huguenot origin): variant of <b>Claremont</b>, from the Old French female personal name <i>Claremonde</i>, supposedly from ancient Germanic <i>Claremunda</i>, a hybrid compound of Latin <i>clarus</i> ‘famous’ + ancient Germanic <i>mund</i> ‘protection’."],"variants":[{"name":"Clairmont","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Aime, Antoine, Aurore, Fernand.","French: variant of   Clermont   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. The surname <i>Clairmont</i> is very rare in France.","In some cases possibly also English: variant of <b>Claremont</b> or   Clermont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel.","Norwegian (<b>Øen</b>): habitational name from the farm name Øen, found in several places. In Hornindal in Nordfjord and in Ål in Hallingdal it is from <i>øy</i> ‘meadow by water’, in Hyllestad in Sunnfjord from <i>å</i> ‘small river’ + Old Norse <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, in other places from the definite singular form of <i>øy</i> ‘island’.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Oen in Hordaland, from Old Norse <i>Ó</i>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Wen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Han, Cheng, Jin, Li, Yen, Yong, Chen, Chih-Hung, Chin, Hong, Jian, Jung, Long, Huan, Hung, Hung Chi, Ly, Quan.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 溫, meaning ‘warm’ in Chinese: (i) from Wen (溫), the name of an ancient state during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ). During the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) this state was annexed by the state of Di and the prince of Wen fled to the state of Wey (located around present-day Hebi and Xinxiang in Henan province). His descendants acquired 溫, the name of their original state, as their surname. (ii) from the placename Wen (溫), the name of a fief granted to Wen Ji (溫季), an official in the state of Jin (located mainly in present-day Shanxi province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the Chi Wen (叱溫), Wen Pen (溫盆), and Wen Gu (溫孤) families of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) from the personal name of Wen Sheng (溫昇), who went into exile and changed his original surname, Liu (劉), to Wen 溫 after his father, Liu Yicong (劉易從), an official in the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), suffered persecution and death."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marguerite de Clermont en Beauvaisis was born in 1105, in Oise, Picardie, France, her father, Renaud de Clermont II, was 24 and her mother, Adélaïde de Vermandois, was 46. She married Baudouin d'Encre in 1135. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. She died after 1145, in Albert, Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1105–after 1145":"1105–pärast 1145","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1098–1161":"1098–1161","–1188":"–1188","–Male":"Surnud","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1148–1214":"1148–1214","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1081–1162":"1081–1162","1059–1120":"1059–1120","23 September 1120":"23. september 1120","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","1098":"1098","1152":"1152","1162":"1162","1161":"1161","1081":"1081","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1203":"1203","1214":"1214","1148":"1148","1103":"1103","1059":"1059","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","after 1145":"pärast 1145","Aisne, Picardie, France":"Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Albert, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Clermont-en-Beauvais, Oise, Picardy, France":"Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1105–after 1145":"1105–1145 jälkeen","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1098–1161":"1098–1161","–1188":"–1188","–Male":"Kuollut","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1148–1214":"1148–1214","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203"